description:
In UnitOfWork.CommitTransactionAsync, the catch block calls RollbackTransactionAsync, and the finally block disposes the transaction:

try {
    await SaveChangesAsync(cancellationToken);
    await _transaction.CommitAsync(cancellationToken);
}
catch (Exception ex) {
    await RollbackTransactionAsync(cancellationToken);  // sets _transaction = null
    throw;
}
finally {
    await _transaction.DisposeAsync();  // NullReferenceException if rollback succeeded
    _transaction = null;
}

If the catch block's RollbackTransactionAsync succeeds, it sets _transaction = null in its finally block. Then CommitTransactionAsync's finally block tries to call DisposeAsync() on null, causing a NullReferenceException that masks the original exception.

If RollbackTransactionAsync throws (because _transaction is already null from a partial failure), it throws InvalidOperationException('No transaction in progress'), which replaces the original commit error.

Fix: In the finally block, use null-conditional: 'if (_transaction != null) { await _transaction.DisposeAsync(); _transaction = null; }'

In both UnitOfWork implementations (TermReader.Persistence and Infrastructure.Persistence), the DisposeAsyncCore method has a logic bug:

protected virtual async ValueTask DisposeAsyncCore()
{
    if (!_disposed && _transaction != null)  // <-- only enters block if transaction exists
    {
        await _transaction.DisposeAsync();
        _transaction = null;
        _disposed = true;  // <-- only set inside the if block
    }
}

If there is no active transaction (the common case, since repositories call SaveChangesAsync directly), _disposed is never set to true in the async path. This means:
1. DisposeAsync() calls DisposeAsyncCore() which does nothing, then calls Dispose(false) which also does nothing (disposing=false).
2. The object is never marked as disposed, so subsequent calls do not detect double-disposal.

While this is not causing active harm since there is nothing else to dispose besides the transaction, it is a correctness bug in the disposal pattern. Fix: Set _disposed=true unconditionally when !_disposed.
